datasource: Hetzron, Robert. 1969. 'The Verbal System of Southern cushitic agaw'. Near Eastern Studies, vol. 12. Los Angeles: University of California Press. [RH69p]
Hetzron, Robert. 1978. The nominal system of Awngi (Southern cushitic agaw). Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies 41. 121–141 [RH78p/t]
datasourceNotes: Note on the organization of RH1969: Awngi verb morphology is organized around a set of core 'tenses': Imperfect and Perfect, Definite and Indefinite, Affirmative and Negative, plus a subordinate Converb form and a Compound form. On the base of this core  is built a highly elaborated tense-aspect-mood  verbal inflection system whose enumeration does not seem to be exhausted in any extant grammar. David Appleyard (19XX p. yyy) estimates that the full paradigm ('scatter') of a verb in the Bilin Agaw might contain more that 10,000 verbal forms. In his masterful 'Verbal System of Southern Agaw' Hetzron devotes his first chapter, 'The Verbal Forms',  to a full listing (seven forms each)  of   65 paradigms for the verb 'desǝŋ' 'study', plus descriptions of the general shape, without a full listing, of a dozen or so more.  Chapter 2, 'Verb Classes',  recognizes some 40 inflectional classes subdividing both the prefix and suffix-conjugation verbs. These are based on intersecting criteria of: 'Pattern' (base tone-pattern), 'Type' (associated png-marker set), and 'Group' (tone-effect on subsequent syllable). Pending a more thorough-going analysis, these classes are taken as brute inflectional classes, and are here designated according to the decimal subdivision of Chapter 2 where each class is identified.  An appendix 'TABLE OF CONJUGATION' gives nine full 'Verbal Form  paradigms' for each of eight  lexical items representative of distinct Pattern-Type-Group configurations.

geodemoTXT: Varieties and subdialects of cushitic agaw (or Central) Cushitic language: Awngi is spoken mainly in the Amhara region, southwest of Lake Tana, and in scattered nearby localities. The variety represented here is that of the village of Bert'a Abbo in the province of cushitic agawmeder, as described by Robert Hetzron in his 1969 monograph.
